“Tombstone” is a strong name. The idea is workable if you treat it less like “hide treasure in the ground” and more like a certified, monitored claim on resources-in-place that the market can actually trust.

Here’s how to make it real without hand-waving.

⸻

🪦 Tombstone (RIP Vault) — grounded blueprint

1) What the asset actually is

* Parcel + subsurface rights (or a legally defined interest)
* Resource estimate with confidence bands (inferred → indicated → measured)
* Extraction constraint (e.g., urban zone, protected area, no-mine covenant)

👉 In cities, you’re not creating ownership out of thin air—you’re:

* partnering with whoever holds subsurface rights, or
* structuring a royalty/lease/option that’s recognized in that jurisdiction

⸻

2) Measurement (no magic sensors—stack methods)

LiDAR helps with surface geometry, but subsurface value needs a stack:

* Seismic / EM / gravity surveys for structure
* Core samples / historical drilling data for grade
* Geostatistical models for volume & uncertainty

Output:

* Estimate + uncertainty range, not a single number

⸻

3) Certification (this is make-or-break)

Use recognized frameworks so capital will touch it:

* SEC reserve reporting (US)
* JORC Code (global analogue)

Independent auditors sign off on:

* methodology
* confidence tier
* periodic updates

⸻

4) Registry + contracts (the tradable layer)

You don’t need secrecy—you need legibility:

* Unique asset ID (parcel + depth interval)
* Ownership/beneficial interest
* Encumbrances:
    * royalties
    * leases
    * options
    * no-extraction covenants (or conditional triggers)

This can live in a standard registry; a blockchain can be an audit trail, not the core trust.

⸻

5) Monitoring (your “Delta Watcher”)

This is your differentiator.

Track deltas across channels over time:

* Satellite (optical + radar) → surface disturbance
* Ground sensors → vibration/anomaly
* Administrative data → permits, utilities, zoning changes

Rules:

* Signal = consistent change across independent channels
* Alert → investigate → enforce via legal agreements

⸻

6) Market design (how value moves)

What gets traded:

* Spot valuation: NPV of in-place resource × confidence discount
* Options: right to develop if constraints change
* Royalties: slice of any future extraction
* Hedges: tie to commodity prices

Why buyers care:

* exposure to resource upside without capex
* environmental positioning (leave-in-ground)
* portfolio diversification

⸻

🏙️ Why “urban / non-minable” zones are interesting

* High likelihood of permanent non-extraction → aligns with preservation markets
* Long-dated option value (technology, policy, or zoning could change decades out)
* Potential to pair with city stakeholders (revenue share, infrastructure funding)

⸻

⚠️ Reality checks (so it doesn’t break)

1. Rights first, tech second
    If you don’t have a recognized legal interest, nothing else matters.
2. Uncertainty is priced
    Markets will haircut estimates heavily unless certification is strong and repeated.
3. “Anonymity” won’t be your security model
    Protection comes from law + monitoring + enforcement, not hiding coordinates.
4. Liquidity requires standardization
    Common reporting tiers, contract templates, and audit cadence.
5. Extraction trigger must be explicit
    Define when/how an asset can move from “vaulted” to “developable.”

